<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-631-841  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 631 841.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Nov 19 1990 v7 n45 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Evans andamp; Sutherland unveils diskless workstations, cuts prices.andO;(the ESV 3) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Evans andamp; Sutherland introduces the ESV 3 diskless graphicsworkstation running at 25 MHz and providing 360,000 vectors persecond and 19,000 polygons per second, according to the company.andO;The $27,900 workstation represents the low end of the ESVworkstation series; a diskless version of the top-end 25-MHz ESV50 priced at $78,400 provides one million vectors or 100,000polygons per second.andP;  Evans andamp; Sutherland also cut the price of theremaining ESV models by 7 to 22 percent and introduces version 1.3of the ESV workstation software.andP;  Also introduced is the FiberLink fiber-optic network interface card costing $9,900 andsupporting the FDDI Network Interface Standard.andP;  Fiber Linkincludes a 68020 processor with 128Kbytes of RAM and 64Kbytes ofPROM, 256Kbytes of packet memory, an Advanced Micro Devices FDDIchip set, optic transceivers and a DMA controller.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Evans and Sutherland Computer Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ESCC.andO;Product:   Evans and Sutherland ESV3 (Workstation) (Product introduction)Evans and Sutherland Fiber Link (Communications board) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     WorkstationsDiskless WorkstationsProduct IntroductionPrice CuttingEnhancementsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardCommunications Boards-CardsLow Cost.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Evans andamp; Sutherland unveils diskless workstations, cuts pricesandM;SALT LAKE CITY--Evans andamp; Sutherland has announced diskless versions of its ESVgraphics workstation series, a low-priced FDDI card, enhancements to ESVworkstation software and a value-added reseller agreement with Eastman Kodakto sell a digital printer.andM;The company has released an entry-level diskless workstation called the ESV3.andP;  It is priced at $27,900 and is the low end of the company's ESV series ofgraphics workstations.andP;  The 25MHz ESV 3 provides 360,000 vectors per secondand 19,000 polygons per second, according to company officials.andM;A diskless version of Evans andamp; Sutherland's top-of-the-line, 25MHz ESV 50 isalso now available.andP;  It is priced at $78,400 and provides 1 million vectorsor 100,000 polygons per second, officials said.andM;In conjunction with the new low-end workstation, the company announced pricereductions for the rest of the ESV line ranging from 7 percent to 22 percent.andM;The company also announced Fiber Link, a fiber-optic network interface cardpriced at $9,900.andM;Fiber Link supports the FDDI Network Interface Standard.andP;  It includes a 68020processor with 128KB of RAM and 64KB of PROM, 256KB of packet memory, anAdvanced Micro Devices FDDI chip set, optic transceivers, and a DMAcontroller.andM;Fiber Link will be available next month, according to officials.andM;Improvements in release 1.3 of the EVS workstation software include theability to switch between seven different video timing formats, andadditional graphics primitives.andP;  The primitives now include spheres,cylinders, triangular strips and quadrilateral meshes.andM;In addition, the software now contains PSXConnect, which allows ESV toemulate a PS 300 graphics terminal.andM;The printer agreement lets Evans andamp; Sutherland resell Eastman Kodak's XL 7700continuous-tone digital printer for use with its ESV workstations.andP;  Theprinter will allow users to print full-color hard copies of 3-D models builton the ESV graphics workstations.andM;The Kodak printer will be available with ESV workstations early next year andis priced at $25,000.andM;Evans andamp; Sutherland has also announced that several additional softwarepackages are being ported to PEX or are now running under PEX.andM;The software includes Evans andamp; Sutherland's Sybyl and CDRS packages, whichwill be available later this month.andM;In addition, Discover and Insight II software from Evans andamp; Sutherland partnerBiosym Technologies of San Diego will be available running under PEX for betatesting in the first quartet of next year.andM;For additional information, Evans andamp; Sutherland Computer Corp. can becontacted at 540 Arapeen Drive, Salt Lake City, UT 84108, (801) 582-5847.andO;</TEXT></DOC>